🧠 What Devs Actually Do With Docker

When teammates use Docker, they are mainly using it for:

1️⃣ Running the Full System Locally (Not Just the App)

Your Spring Boot app rarely runs alone.
It depends on: MySQL, Redis, Kafka, Elasticsearch and Another microservice.

Without Docker:
They must install all these manually.

With Docker:
They run:
docker compose up

Boom 💥
Full backend ecosystem is running.

That’s the real use.

🏗 Real Example

Imagine your project:

springboot-app
├── MySQL
├── Redis
├── Kafka

Without Docker:
Each dev must: Install MySQL, Install Redis, Install Kafka, Configure ports and Configure credentials

That’s painful.

With Docker:

version: '3'
services:
  app:
    build: .
  mysql:
    image: mysql:8
  redis:
    image: redis

Now every developer runs identical infrastructure.

Question: I have created a Spring Boot application and that I have pushed into the Docker Hub and someone in my team pulls it in his system and wants to execute some commands 
or something, then will there be any dependency conflict when he is developing into my app and how will the merge conflicts will be solved?
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

❓ Dependency conflicts

✅ Part 1: Will There Be Dependency Conflicts?
🐳 If You Pushed a Docker Image to Docker Hub

Example flow:

You:
docker build -t ranjeeta/springboot-app .
docker push ranjeeta/springboot-app

Teammate:
docker pull ranjeeta/springboot-app
docker run -p 8080:8080 ranjeeta/springboot-app

🔹 Will there be dependency conflict?
👉 NO. Zero conflict.

Why?
Because your Docker image already contains:
JDK version, Spring Boot version, All Maven dependencies, OS layer (e.g., Ubuntu / Alpine) and App jar

Your teammate is running your exact environment, not rebuilding it.
Docker ensures:
Same image → Same environment → Same behavior

So:
No “Java version mismatch”
No “It works on my machine”
No library conflicts

⚠ Important Difference
If teammate just clones Git repo and runs locally (without Docker)

Then conflicts can happen:
Different JDK (17 vs 21)
Different Maven version
Different DB version
Different OS behavior

Docker solves this by freezing environment.


✅ Part 2: What If Teammate Wants to Develop?

Now we enter a different topic.
There are 2 cases:

🔹 CASE 1: Teammate Just Runs the Image

He cannot modify your code inside image permanently.

Because:
Docker image is read-only
Container changes disappear when deleted (unless committed)  ::::so container  changes does happen

So Docker image is for:
Running / Deploying
Not for collaboration development
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
                                                                         CONTAINER CHANGES

🔒 No, people should NOT change code inside a running container.
But technically… they can. Let’s understand properly.

🐳 1️⃣ Can Someone Change Code Inside a Container?
Yes, they can enter the container:
docker exec -it <container_id> bash
Then they can:

Edit files
Install packages
Modify code

BUT 👇

❌ 2️⃣ Why This Is a Bad Practice

Because containers are:
🔥 Ephemeral (temporary)

If the container is:
Stopped
Deleted
Recreated
All changes are lost.

Example:

docker rm <container_id>
docker run springboot-dev

Now it's back to original state.

So changing container code is:
Not version controlled
Not shareable
Not reproducible
Not professional

🧱 3️⃣ Important Concept: Image vs Container

Think like this:

Image	                Container
Blueprint            	Running instance
Read-only	            Writable layer
Stored permanently	  Temporary

You NEVER change image directly.
You rebuild image.

🏗 Real Development Workflow

Correct way if teammate wants to modify code:
Clone Git repo
Change source code
Commit & push to branch
Build new Docker image
Run container from new image

Like this:

docker build -t springboot-dev .
docker run springboot-dev
[🐳 1️⃣ docker build -t springboot-dev .
What this means:

docker build → Build a Docker image
-t springboot-dev → Tag (name) the image as springboot-dev
. → Use current folder as build context

What actually happens internally?
Docker looks for a file named Dockerfile in current folder -> It reads instructions line by line -> It pulls the base image (if not already present) ->It copies your project files ->
It runs build commands (like mvn clean package) -> It creates a new image named springboot-dev.

After this command finishes:
👉 You now have a Docker image stored locally.

You can check:
docker images

🐳 2️⃣ docker run springboot-dev

This means:
Create a container from the image and start it.

What happens internally:
Docker creates a container from springboot-dev image.
It executes the default command defined in Dockerfile.
Example:
ENTRYPOINT ["java","-jar","app.jar"]
Your Spring Boot app starts inside the container.
]

🧠 4️⃣ What Happens If They Modify Container and Commit It?

Yes, Docker allows:
docker commit <container_id> new-image-name
But this is:
🚫 Not used in real projects
🚫 Not clean
🚫 Not reproducible

Because:
No Dockerfile change
No Git change
No CI tracking
It becomes “manual hack”.

🏢 How Companies Do It (Proper DevOps)

Flow:
Developer → Git → CI → Docker Build → Push Image → Deploy
Nobody edits containers in production.

🔥 Special Case: Live Development with Volume Mount

During development, you can do:
docker run -v $(pwd):/app springboot-dev

Now:

Your local code folder is mounted inside container
If you edit code locally → container sees change
This is proper development approach.
Not editing container manually.

🎯 Final Clear Answer

👉 Can someone change container code?
Yes.
👉 Should they?
No.
👉 Why?
Because containers are temporary and not version-controlled.
👉 What is correct way?
Change source code → rebuild image → run new container.

💡Containers are meant to be immutable. Any code changes should be done in the source repository and a new image should be built rather than modifying a running container.
