🔹 Case 2: Team Collaboration (Real Development Scenario)

In real companies:
You don't collaborate using Docker Hub images.
You collaborate using:
Git
GitHub / GitLab / Bitbucket

Correct Flow:

Code is stored in Git repository -> Everyone pulls code -> Makes changes -> Pushes to branches -> Merge via Pull Request -> CI/CD builds Docker image -> Image pushed to Docker Hub.

So:

Docker = Deployment artifact
Git = Collaboration tool

❓ Merge conflicts
🔥 Now Let’s Talk About Merge Conflicts

Merge conflicts happen in:

Git
Source code

Not in Docker

Example:

You modify:

public String getName() {
    return "Ranjeeta";
}

Teammate modifies same method:

public String getName() {
    return "Team Member";
}

When merging → conflict happens.

Git shows:

<<<<<<< HEAD
return "Ranjeeta";
=======
return "Team Member";
>>>>>>> branch-name

You manually decide which version to keep.

Docker has nothing to do with this.

🧠 Important Understanding
Concern                   	Handled By
Dependency conflicts	      Docker
Environment consistency	    Docker
Code collaboration	        Git
Merge conflicts	            Git
Deployment	                Docker
Scaling	                    Kubernetes


🏗 Real Company Architecture

Real flow: Developer → Git Push → CI builds Docker image → Push to Docker Hub → Deploy

🚀 Now Very Important Scenario

What if teammate wants to modify your app and run locally?

Best approach:
He should:

Clone Git repo
Modify code
Use Docker to build locally:

STEP 1: What Exists in the Git Repo?

Your Git repository usually contains:

springboot-app/
 ├── src/
 ├── pom.xml
 ├── Dockerfile
 ├── mvnw
 └── target/ (after build)

The most important file for Docker is:

👉 Dockerfile

STEP 2: What Is Inside Dockerfile?

Example Dockerfile for Spring Boot:

FROM maven:3.9-eclipse-temurin-17
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
RUN mvn clean package -DskipTests
CMD ["java", "-jar", "target/app.jar"]

Now let’s understand what happens when teammate runs:

docker build -t springboot-dev .

STEP 3: What Actually Happens During docker build?

When this command runs:

docker build -t springboot-dev .

Docker does this:

1️⃣ Reads Dockerfile

Docker checks instructions line by line.

2️⃣ Pulls Base Image (if not present)
FROM maven:3.9-eclipse-temurin-17

Docker checks:

Is this image already on my machine?

YES → Use it

NO → Download from Docker Hub

This image already contains: Linux OS, Maven installed, JDK 17 installed

So teammate does NOT need to install Java or Maven manually.

3️⃣ Creates Temporary Build Container

Docker creates a temporary container and executes:

WORKDIR /app
COPY . .

It copies the cloned Git project into the container.

4️⃣ Runs Maven Inside Container
RUN mvn clean package -DskipTests

Now Maven runs inside the container, not on teammate's machine.

It:

Downloads dependencies from Maven Central
Builds the jar
Stores it in /app/target/app.jar

Even if teammate:

Has no Java installed
Has wrong Java version
Has no Maven
It still works.
Because everything is inside container.

5️⃣ Image Is Created

After build completes:

Docker creates a new image called:
springboot-dev

This image contains:
OS layer
JDK
Maven
Your compiled jar
Dependencies

STEP 4: When Teammate Runs
docker run -p 8080:8080 springboot-dev

Docker:
Creates container from image

Executes:
java -jar target/app.jar
App starts.

🧩 Docker is NOT building using your system.
It is building inside:
A temporary container created from the base image.

That’s why:
No dependency conflict
No JDK mismatch
No Maven version issue

📦 Visual Flow

Flow:

Git Clone → Dockerfile → Pull base image → Copy code → Run build → Create image → Run container

🔎 Very Important: Multi-Stage Build (Professional Way)

Real projects use:

# Stage 1 - Build
FROM maven:3.9-eclipse-temurin-17 AS build
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
RUN mvn clean package -DskipTests

# Stage 2 - Runtime
FROM eclipse-temurin:17-jdk
WORKDIR /app
COPY --from=build /app/target/app.jar app.jar
ENTRYPOINT ["java","-jar","app.jar"]

Why?

Because final image:

Does NOT contain Maven

Is smaller

More secure

🎯 Final Simple Explanation

When teammate runs:

docker build .

Docker:

Pulls base image (with Java/Maven)

Copies project code

Runs build inside container

Creates new image

Everything happens inside Docker’s isolated environment.

Your local system doesn’t matter

docker build -t springboot-dev .
docker run -p 8080:8080 springboot-dev

So everyone builds image from same Dockerfile.

🧩 Advanced Concept (Very Important)

If you design your Dockerfile properly:

Example:

FROM openjdk:17-jdk-slim
COPY target/app.jar app.jar
ENTRYPOINT ["java", "-jar", "app.jar"]

Then dependency resolution happens at:

Maven build time

Not at runtime

So image is stable.

🔥 Final Clear Answer

If teammate pulls your Docker image:

✅ No dependency conflict
❌ No merge conflict (because no code change)

If teammate clones Git and modifies code:

⚠ Merge conflicts handled by Git
⚠ Dependency conflicts avoided by Dockerfile consistency

🎯 Docker prevents dependency conflicts by packaging the application with its runtime and dependencies inside an image.
However, merge conflicts are related to version control systems like Git and are resolved during code merging, not through Docker.
